    {
      "id": "816a2c7361a7819eb6b85bbce510130feb1881b8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2014-06-26 16:39:10.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.5/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/47f610e2-fd50-11e3-b84d-5254006e85c2).  Ran 6 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e87bb043b2a9c83cfc23a05338932d52565292f1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-06-26 17:12:27.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "0f844b375e06fcf9e678556533bc95d87dbabdf7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 148,
        "name": "Chris Horn",
        "email": "chris.horn@hpe.com",
        "username": "hornc"
      },
      "date": "2014-06-26 18:01:55.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThe bug fix looks correct to me, but I think we should do more to reflect the semantic change introduced by LU-5259\n\nptlrpc_client_recv_or_unlink() used to indicate whether the reply buffer has been unlinked, but with LU-5259 this is no longer completely true. If we get 0 back we know the reply buffer has been unlinked, but if we get 1 back the reply buffer might still be unlinked (or it might not). It seems to me that ptlrpc_unregister_reply() only needs to know whether the reply has been unlinked, but ptlrpc_check_set() needs to know that LNET has dropped its reference on both the reply and outgoing buffer.\n\nI think we should make this distinction clear in the code. At the very least we should edit/add comments to make this clear, or, ideally, we should change the code.\n\nWe could remove rq_req_unlink from ptlrpc_client_recv_or_unlink and explicitly check it in ptlrpc_check_set where appropriate, so ptlrpc_client_recv_or_unlink goes back to its original meaning.\n\nWe could add an additional inline function that checks all three variables and use that in ptlrpc_check_set() instead of ptlrpc_client_recv_or_unlink (ptlrpc_client_all_unlink or something?).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "56baffca871beb64c09f01a13eb70e0b13442b6c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2014-06-26 19:26:56.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.5/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/a5e0636c-fd67-11e3-a01a-5254006e85c2).  Ran 13 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e39467cce29028a498d2e2573b9eca9cedf7dbb0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
